<TEXT>
critics called him a pharoah and said he would 
resurrect the machine politics of his late father but one month 
after his inauguration even some detractors praise mayor richard 
m daley for his political shrewdness 
since taking the oath of office on his 47th birthday april 24 
daley has ordered a televisionworthy cleanup of city hall which 
he likened to a pig pen and called for appointment of an 
ethics watchdog with subpoena power to root out corruption among 
all city employees even aldermen 
he also cut more than 40 million from planned city spending 
and broke with tradition by ordering parked cars some driven by 
city honchos towed from illegal spaces surrounding city hall even 
his press secretary found her car missing 
and saying he didnt want to be the only survivor of a nuclear 
attack he pledged to sell a new 50000 bulletproof mayoral 
limousine ordered before he took office 
visible reforms make good ink said don rose a political 
activist and longtime daley critic who worked for alderman timothy 
evans daleys independent challenger in the april 4 election 
those are public relations nice attentiongetting moves 
rose said calling some of the actions selfserving i think i 
have to say whatever the motives hes gotten off on the right 
foot 
but rose added we havent seen any of the real actions of 
government yet and im still very very wary of what his policies 
are going to be 
daley faces reelection in the spring of 1991 leading some 
detractors to call the mayors actions mere campaign tactics but 
marj halperin a spokeswoman for the mayor defends his moves 
i keep wondering when people will finally understand that this 
is real she said tuesday these arent things you do just for 
show these are things you do to manage the city responsibly and 
effectively 
daley son of the late boss of chicago richard j daley 
defeated evans who is black and democratturnedrepublican edward 
vrdolyak april 4 for the right to finish out the last two years of 
the second term of the late mayor harold washington who died in 
office in 1987 
washington was the citys first black mayor and the city 
council elected eugene sawyer a black south side alderman to be 
interim mayor following washingtons death daley defeated sawyer 
in the democratic primary in february 
evans who called daley a pharoah at the beginning of the 
campaign has criticized the mayors performance as lackluster 
daley made a campaign promise that he would always look to 
collecting revenue already owed to the city before he would raise 
taxes evans said yet the first thing he did was to raise 
water and sewer taxes 
the increase was drafted under sawyer but passed under daley 
we did reduce it from the previous administration halperin 
said 
tom roesser president of the city club of chicago and a 
political analyst close to the gop said daley is doing what most 
politicians do while facing the next election 
i see nothing nefarious or hollow or not serious at all he 
said im amazed frankly at how much reform he has brought 
david orr a white alderman who supported evans said he has 
been pleased with daleys reforms and a push for city efficiency 
theres still a part of me thats surprised at his political 
astuteness in the last few weeks orr said i think it sets a 
critical tone 
