<TEXT>
raising excise taxes to reduce the federal 
deficit would impose an unfair burden on rural americans who 
already pay onethird more of their earnings for such taxes than do 
city dwellers two economists said today 
economists james long and robert ekelund of auburn university in 
alabama said they found that rural households at every income level 
up to 40000 spend a bigger share of their earnings on excise 
taxes on motor fuel tobacco and utilities 
this differential tends to be greatest at lowincome levels 
long said at a news conference sponsored by the american 
agriculture movement which sponsored the study 
if this congress starts looking at an increase in excise taxes 
as a way to balance the budget we want to say no way said 
david senter national director of the 35state farm group 
several members of congress have suggested raising federal taxes 
on gasoline alcoholic beverages and cigarattes as ways of cutting 
the budget deficit rep dan rostenkowski dill chairman of the 
house ways and means committee advocates a sharp increase in the 
gasoline tax but only if president bush agrees to go along 
there are mounting indications that congress will approve no 
general tax increase this year but lawmakers of both parties 
already are talking of the need for higher taxes a year from now 
long and ekelund concluded that the excise burden on rural 
families is 49 percent higher on gasoline 41 percent higher on 
tobacco products and 21 percent higher on utilities fuels and 
public services 
rural americans pay 7 percent less of their income on alcoholic 
beverages than do others but that difference would likely be 
reversed when weighted for beer consumption they wrote 
using the governments consumer expenditure survey for 1984 as a 
basis the economists found for example that a rural family with 
income between 10000 and 20000 paid 402 in federal excises 
while the urban family paid 335 at 20000 to 30000 income 
rural families outspent urban families 461 to 429 rural families 
between 30000 and 40000 were taxed for 523 compared with 486 
for urban families 
the study assumes families living outside an area with 2500 
population or more are rural that covers about 40 million 
americans 
</TEXT>
