<TEXT>
many scientists at a workshop set up to 
investigate cold fusion say they will keep looking for evidence of 
the process but nearly all of them say they have seen no sign yet 
it exists 
the workshop on the claims of university of utah chemist stanley 
pons and his british colleague martin fleischmann has brought 
together an estimated 500 physicists and chemists with a wide 
variety of theories 
pons and fleischmann startled the scientific world with the 
announcement two months ago that they had achieved cold fusion in a 
simple experiment using a palladium electrode and water made with 
deuterium a heavy isotope of hydrogen 
the conventional belief was that fusion as an energy source 
could be attained only at high temperatures and by applying high 
power 
the announcement has been the subjects of several conferences 
around the country including the threeday workshop here the 
workshop sponsored by los alamos national laboratory concludes 
thursday 
there seems to be an intense scientific interest in the 
possibility that a nuclear reaction takes place in a sofar 
unanticipated site said norman hackerman retired professor of 
chemistry at rice and texas universities 
pons and fleischmann ignored the opportunity to attend the 
workshop and defend their claims they also canceled a meeting with 
utah officials who want to give them 5 million for their research 
the observations at the conference included many like those of 
physicist nathan lewis of the california institute of technology 
he flatly rejected the ponsfleischmann assertions 
hopeful commentary came from texas aampm university chemist john 
appleby he suggested that fusion has sometimes occurred in his 
teams experiment 
appleby declined to say in an interview that fusion occurred in 
the ponsfleischmann experiments if it is fusion he said it is 
not occurring in the usual way 
fusion is a process in which light atoms combine to form heavier 
elements releasing energy 
applebys encouraging findings included the discovery of large 
amounts of tritium in the heavy water solution along with a small 
number of neutrons tritium can be a product of fusion 
he also described different heat measurements using different 
solutions such as a lithiumbased bath and a sodium solution that 
shut down all reactions 
we dont know whats going on but it is not chemistry 
appleby said theres a lot of confusion rather than fusion 
going on 
petar tomas a physicist with the ruder boskovic institute in 
yugoslavia said he found the utah claims difficult to believe 
but he proclaimed much of the theoretical physics presented at the 
workshop positive and headed in the right direction 
</TEXT>
