<TEXT>
the fueleconomy standard for 1989 passenger 
cars will remain at 265 miles per gallon the national highway 
traffic safety administration said wednesday in rejecting a 
petition for reconsideration of the regulation 
the petition filed by two washingtonbased advocacy groups the 
center for auto safety and public citizen asked nhtsa to allow the 
corporate average fuel economy standard to revert to 275 mpg the 
level set by a 1975 law intended to reduce dependence on foreign 
oil 
the advocacy groups failed to make a case that the standard 
should have been set at a level other than 265 mpg nhtsas 
order said 
in their petition the organizations argued that contrary to 
nhtsas findings congress fueleconomy goals remaned unmet the 
organizations said nhtsa erred in determining that general motors 
corp the worlds largest automaker could only meet at 265 mpg 
standard and in blaming declining gm sales on the fueleconomy 
standards 
the petition put nhtsa in a position of defending the 265 mpg 
fueleconomy standard after transportation secretary samuel skinner 
said last week he would allow the standard to revert to 275 mpg 
for the 1990 model year skinner said then he hoped the stiffer 
standard would encourage the automakers to make more efficient cars 
if the agency had applied the same standards to 1989 as it did 
to 1990 it would have kept the standard at 275 mpg said 
clarence ditlow director of the center for auto safety todays 
decision is simply inconsistent with last weeks decision by 
secretary skinner one of the two decisions has to be wrong and 
were sure secretary skinner was wrong this week and right last 
week 
the fuel economy standards require each automakers fleet of 
passenger cars on average to attain a certain gas mileage 
the 1975 law set a gradually rising scale of fuel economy that 
must be met with the goal of reaching 275 mpg but also allowed 
nhtsas parent agency the transportation department to loosen the 
minimum standard through administrative order to account for 
economic and technical factors 
the standard was loosened under that provision to 26 mpg in 1986 
at the request of the automakers and remained there until 1989 
</TEXT>
