<TEXT>
a hard winter and 
extended hunting season produced a decline of almost 40 percent in 
yellowstone national parks northern elk herd according to 
biologists 
harvest of the animals during regular and lateseason hunting 
accounted for 14 percent to 16 percent mortality and 24 percent to 
27 percent of the herd died from winter exposure the biologists 
said 
earlier this year yellowstone biologist frank singer had 
estimated that roughly onethird of the northern herd would die 
either from hunting or the winter weather however by early march 
nearly onefourth of the herd had already died 
a report issued by the biologists tuesday said last years 
forest fires and drought were followed by a winter of snow that 
ranged from 95 percent to 110 percent of normal three separate 
arctic cold fronts contributed to the winter kill the biologists 
said 
studies of carcasses this spring indicated that most of the dead 
elk were either elderly or calves 
a large number of the survivors are primeage reproductive 
animals the report said 
they said elk died in greater numbers than mule deer and 
antelope because no mule deer or antelope winter range was burned 
by the fires 
the biologists based their figures on aerial counts of the herd 
yellowstones largest in early winter the population was estimated 
at 18506 to 20358 head while on jan 26 the number fell between 
17207 and 19059 
counts in april following montanas lateseason elk hunt outside 
the park placed the herds population between 11801 and 13137 
animals according to the biologists the counts suggested that 
almost 5000 elk died from winter kill alone 
singer and fellow biologist tom lemke of the montana department 
of fish wildlife and parks said in their report that it is 
impossible to separate the effects of drought and the fires of 
1988 upon elk since both factors affected summer and winter 
range 
yellowstone officials said wednesday they havent established 
any average mortality rate for the herd because they have conducted 
serious elk research only in the past couple years 
