<TEXT>
a house subcommittee on wednesday approved a 
bill giving the federal government authority to determine damages 
to be paid by oil companies after spills 
the measure approved by the house merchant marine and fisheries 
coast guard subcommittee bars states from enacting stricter damage 
laws than the federal standard 
the issue of state versus federal standard has been the chief 
hurdle over the past 13 years blocking legislation to simplify 
existing oil spill laws the oil industry has favored having the 
federal government set damages 
while the house has repeatedly passed bills allowing federal 
standards the senate has insisted that states be permitted to have 
stricter standards 
the chief senate supporter of that position has been senate 
majority leader george mitchell dmaine who has introduced a 
liability bill 
the march 24 oil spill of the exxon valdez in alaska has given 
new impetus to attempts to reach a compromise 
i think for the first time we have an incredible momentum for 
a bill said rep w j billy tauzin dla chairman of the 
house subcommittee 
he explained that changes in wording may make the house measure 
more acceptable to past opponents 
states can now tax oil companies to obtain the money needed to 
clean up spills if the bill is approved the federal government 
would create by a cleanup fund bankrolled by a 13 cent per barrel 
tax on all imported oil 
the bill is one of several in congress spawned by the exxon 
valdez accident the nations worstever oil spill the giant 
tanker hit a wellmarked reef pouring 11 million gallons of crude 
oil into pristine prince william sound 
the subcommittee also the prince william sound oil spill 
response act which calls for better surveillance of vessels in 
prince william sound and stronger safety measures in case of a 
spill 
the bill says a persons license to operate a vessel in the 
sound could be revoked if the individual was convicted of violating 
alcohol abuse laws it states that licenses will not be issued or 
renewed if the person is a chronic alcohol abuser 
exxon announced march 31 that it had fired the exxon valdez 
captain joseph hazelwood after federal investigators reported 
that his blood alcohol level was well above the coast guard maximum 
10 hours after the accident it was revealed that hazelwood had a 
history of drunken driving convictions 
