a joint panel on sensitive areas in 
polishsoviet history says the soviet foreign ministers comments 
after poland was invaded in 1939 were contradictory to 
international law and offensive to poland 
a report called origins and beginning of world war ii was 
published wednesday in the communist party newspaper trybuna ludu 
which said it appeared simultaneously in pravda the soviet party 
newspaper 
it includes a reference to the aug 23 1939 hitlerstalin 
nonaggression pact and the secret protocol attached to it defining 
how the nazis and soviets would divide poland 
world war ii began with the german invasion of poland sept 1 
1939 the day after the supreme soviet ratified the agreement 
soviet soldiers invaded from the east sept 17 
foreign minister vyacheslav molotov told the supreme soviet a 
month later that the two armies had wiped out this grotesque 
product of the treaty of versailles the report said 
molotovs statement was contradictory to international law and 
offensive to poland the report declared the present soviet 
leadership and the scientific community of the soviet union 
distance themselves decisively from it 
western historians learned of the secret protocol from captured 
nazi documents the report published wednesday said the original 
could not be found in soviet or other archives 
it also said a soviet goverment statement handed to the polish 
ambassador sept 17 1939 declaring the polish state to be no 
longer in existence was discrepant with the norms of 
international law 
that statement said soviet forces entered poland only to protect 
the inhabitants of western byelorussia and the ukraine 
the course of events connected with the movement of the red 
army in september 1939 to the west requires more detailed 
historical studies the joint report said 
