<TEXT>
with asking prices below their highs of a few 
months ago with large numbers of unsold houses on the market and 
with interest rates falling an investment opportunity may be 
developing in singlefamily housing 
while such opportunities are more common in housing than in most 
markets partly because housing is made up of a greater percentage 
of amateur versus professional sellers as in cars they are 
transitory 
in fact as soon as such opportunities appear they begin to 
vanish thats the housing market for you up and down more sharply 
than other markets and always exaggerating the usual economic 
cycle bust to boom and back to bust 
the most important element in the opening for buyers is the 
general decline of interest rates which many forecasters expect 
will continue right through the year 
interest rates are key since interest is the biggest housing 
expense for those who take out 20year or 30year mortgages 
sometimes equalling the total cost of all other factors including 
land and the structure itself 
when you have a combination of lower rates and relatively softer 
prices asking prices that are below their earlier highs or that 
are negotiable you have a buying opportunity now add to that a 
big inventory of unsold units 
earlier this year the national association of realtors 
estimated the inventory of unsold homes at more than 29 million 
units or a ninemonth supply of existing homes and 75month 
supply of new houses 
what that means is a lot of unhappy sellers while they could 
rationalize the inattention given to their offerings during the 
winter when weather and mood keep people from shopping they are 
now in the prime selling months 
another factor enters the picture the news about housing has a 
rather dismal cast of late just a month or two ago for example 
sellers and buyers were loudly lamenting the deadly duo of rising 
prices and interest rates 
in many areas those factors have changed in some they have 
been reversed but the mood lingers keeping many potential buyers 
from the market it is of course a situation that can change 
overnight it has happened before 
still another factor is involved in the potential investment 
opportunity if the price of the house purchased today is to have 
greater market value tomorrow it would help tremendously if future 
housing were in short supply 
there is no proof that such a situation will develop but it 
should be noted that the number of residential building permits 
issued in 1989 could be the lowest in seven years future demand 
therefore might not be met 
the national association of home builders forecasts 102 million 
singlefamily housing starts this year a figure that would make 
1989 the weakest homebuilding year since 1983 lomas mortgage usa 
a large mortgage lender estimates new housing permits this year at 
1394 million 21 percent lower than in 1986 
building activity today creates tomorrows markets and if 
building this year is weak it could tip tomorrows buyerseller 
balance those who buy today that is conceivably could find 
market values higher a few years hence 
