<TEXT>
if you sometimes think the daily grind is a 
dogeatdog world you ought to see what goes on between the fungi 
and the pathogens 
of course says the agriculture department there are good 
fungi but there are also bad fungi pathogens theyre the tiny 
things like viruses that cause diseases and theyre mostly bad 
the idea of using natures own organisms to fight hold back and 
destroy plant diseases has been around a long time and the 
departments agricultural research service says the search 
continues for biological ways of protecting crops 
recent reports from the agency show the task to be slow and 
painstaking fungi and bacteria exist naturally in the same soil 
that nourishes corn wheat rice cotton soybeans and even 
backyard tomatoes 
one of the tasks of the scientists is to sort out those 
organisms and choose through experiments the ones that can help 
protect crops 
twenty years from now well have many more biological 
controls like fungi to use says deborah r fravel an agency 
plant pathologist they may not be as common as chemicals but 
they certainly will be increasingly important i dont think 
biological controls will ever completely replace chemicals but 
they will help reduce the amount of chemicals used 
half a dozen beneficial fungi are being studied at the agencys 
biocontrol of plant diseases laboratory in nearby beltsville md 
where fravel works each is under scrutiny for its ability to fight 
pathogens such as the bad fungi bacteria microscopic worms called 
nematodes and even viruses 
the idea is that we can enhance whats out there in nature 
fravel said a lot of management practices in use right now such 
as adding organic matter to the soil actually are biocontrols 
because organic matter feeds the organisms already in place 
fungi used in biocontrol fight plant pathogens in several ways 
parasitism or actually feeding on the pathogen antibiosis or 
producing some sort of compound that is toxic to the pathogen and 
through competition the most common action 
for example she said plant roots leak carbon sources such as 
sugar the biocontrol organisms get to those carbon sources before 
the pathogens do so the pathogens cant get anything to eat and 
cant grow or the biocontrol organisms may simply occupy all the 
space around the root so the pathogen cant get in 
fravel and her colleagues are conducting tests in some new 
jersey eggplant fields to see how well a beneficial fungus 
talaromyces flavus fights verticillium wilt disease in previous 
field tests the fungus in combination with a reduced amount of 
chemical fumigant reduced wilt disease in eggplant crops by as much 
as 75 percent 
jack a lewis a soil scientist at the beltsville laboratory 
said work recently began on encasing two other fungi trichoderma 
and gliocladium in pellets which then are mixed into infected 
soil or potting material to test their effectiveness 
the pellets contain food for the biocontrol fungi lewis 
said the organism grows out of the pellet and spreads through 
the soil where it attacks the pathogen and kills it 
a number of other fungi also are being studied as possible 
weapons including some that might be targeted against pathogens 
that help cause the rotting of seed and the seedlings of cotton 
sugarbeets and many vegetables and ornamental plants 
still other fungi are being used experimentally against some of 
their bad relatives noted for causing stalk rot in corn 
plant pathologist nader g vakili who works at the usda 
agencys cereal and soybean improvement research unit in ames 
iowa said the good fungi enter and live inside the corn plant 
where they eat away at the rot fungi 
vakili sprayed spores of melanospora damnosa on corn plants in 
test plots in the first year the beneficial fungus infected only 
about onehalf of 1 percent of the stalk rot fungus fusarium 
moniliforme in the stalks but after five years as the good 
fungus built up in the soil 50 percent to 80 percent were infected 
the results suggest that strains of biocontrol fungi could be 
selected for compatability with specific lines of corn he said 
the corn would be bred to support large numbers of the fungi 
organisms 
in the us alone stalk rots reduce yields by some 500 
million bushels annually vakili said 
but fungi are not the only weapons being looked at by usda 
scientists chemist jeffrey s buyer and two colleagues have 
produced and tested a monoclonal antibody a custombuilt protein 
that will seek out and fasten onto ironhoarding compounds called 
siderophores 
virtually all bacteria and fungi good and bad alike produce 
siderophores to meet their own iron needs buyer said sometimes 
but not always these compounds help control pathogens 
right now we have no good methods to study the compounds in 
their natural state or determine why they sometimes do and 
sometimes dont help control disease organisms buyer said 
the new antibody which is headed for greenhouse tests this 
summer on roots of barley seedlings hopefully will seek and bind 
to siderophores so they can be measured and studied more fully 
eventually it may be possible for farmers and home gardeners to 
make bad microbes anemic by loading the soil with certain 
beneficial bacteria that will deprive the pathogens of their iron 
supply 
</TEXT>
