beecham group plc a major british pharmaceutical 
company wednesday reported a 19 percent profit increase for its 
fiscal year with the best growth coming from prescription drugs 
beecham which has proposed merging with smithkline beckman 
corp of the united states said its aftertax profit for the 12 
months ended march 31 came to 301 million pounds or about 473 
million up from 252 million pounds or 396 million in the prior 
year 
earnings per share were 3973 pence or 62 cents and 3334 
pence or 52 cents in the same respective years 
revenue grew 1 percent to 251 billion pounds or 394 billion 
from the prior years 248 billion pounds or 389 billion 
the earnings results coincided with beechams mailing to its 
shareholders of the formal document setting out the terms of its 
merger agreement with smithkline 
the merger on which beecham shareholders are to vote june 20 
would create a combined company with annual sales of more than 67 
billion ranking it second only to merck and co of the united 
states among world pharmaceutical companies 
beecham said prescription drugs contributed strongly to its 
profit with the best growth coming from sales of newer higher 
margin products such as the antibiotics augmentin and timentin but 
sales of amoxil beechams longstanding antibiotic which is facing 
generic drug competition were flat 
beecham didnt break out results for its fourth quarter or the 
second half of its fiscal year it isnt required to do so under 
british law 
