<TEXT>
house lawmakers wednesday lashed out at fax 
attacks by advertisers who bombard facsimile machines with 
unsolicited material and they said telephone merchandisers who use 
computers to dial phone numbers at random could endanger public 
health and safety 
the lawmakers said advertisers were shooting themselves in the 
foot with intrusive sales pitches that in the case of facsimiles 
use up their receivers paper and for mobile and pagerphone users 
often make them pay for the calls 
on top of that citizens have a right to privacy said rep 
barney frank dmass the author of one of three bills that would 
restrain the use of junk fax advertising and computer 
autodialers 
frank told a hearing of the house energy and commerce 
telecommunications and finance subcommittee that it was stupid 
to assert that restrictions on unsolicited telepone messages would 
violate the senders first amendment rights 
were saying that you cant use technology to burden other 
people frank testified were not putting anybody out of 
business were not interfering with anybodys rights 
the subcommittee chairman rep edward markey dmass said 
unsolicited telemarketing increasingly crosses the line between 
helpful and unacceptably obtrusive 
he noted that in massachusetts 200000 phone customers 7 
percent of the states total said yes recently when asked if they 
wished to be excluded from such calls 
computers can dial 1000 phone numbers a day with prerecorded 
messages markey said 
each day they are used by more than 180000 solicitors to call 
more than 7 million americans unfortunately these machines are 
often programmed to dial sequentially whole blocks of numbers 
including hospitals fire stations pagers and unlisted numbers 
this not only makes the machine an equal opportunity nuisance 
but an equal opportunity hazard markey said 
franks bill would make it illegal to make interstate 
computerdialed calls to anyone who told their phone company they 
didnt want such messages it would require advertisers to pay the 
costs for phone companies to maintain lists of such customers 
a bill cosponsored by markey frank and reps matthew rinaldo 
christopher shays rconn and pete stark dcalif would require 
the same for unsolicited messages to facsimile machines 
a bill by rep marge roukema rnj would make autodialed 
solicitations illegal unless the calls were placed between 9 am 
and 5 pm weekdays the messages gave the name and telephone 
number of the caller and the computer automatically disconnected 
the call five seconds after the called party hangs up or refuses to 
hear the message 
rinaldo said telephone lines have become life lines for 
businesses and citizens particularly the elderly abuses of phone 
lines not only are inconvenient and costly to consumers they 
even could endanger the lives of our citizens 
tying up emergency phones lines with autodialers that wont 
disconnect clearly has the potential for disaster rinaldo 
said there may be legitimate purposes for which autodialers can 
be used however they should not be permitted to endanger the 
usefulness of the telephone 
richard barton a vice president with the direct marketing 
association told the subcommittee his group was sympathetic to 
the concerns expressed by the bills 
he said his group opposes sequential dialing by telemarketers 
and it favored standards that would require immediate disconnects 
but he said it would be very difficult to define as markeys bill 
requires unsolicited messages and what constitutes a 
preexisting business relationship that would allow 
transmission of unsolicited material to offices 
he said there also were about 1000 directories of facsimile 
machine phone numbers and it would be difficult and costly to 
purge them of names 
he urged the subcommittee to let the marketplace decide if 
unsolicited facsimile ads were going to be anything more than a 
shortlived phenomenon 
professor robert ellis of the indiana university school of law 
said many businesses want to receive ads from sellers they deal 
with regularly he said restrictions could chill normal 
business correspondence 
